            <div facs="ia:encyclopediabrit15newyrich/page/n145/mode/1up" type="entry">
                <p><label type="entry">MACCABEES</label>. The name Maccabee (Mακκαβα7os) is properly
                    and originally the distinguishing surname of Judas, son of Mattathias, the first
                    great hero of the Jewish revolt against Antiochus Epiphanes. The source of the
                    name is uncertain, but it is most natural to connect it with 2^0, “hammer,” and
                    so the Syriac writes the name with p not 3. Ewald <hi rend="italic"
                    >(Gesch.,</hi> iv. 403) is doubtless right in arguing from 1 Mac. vi. 43,
                    &amp;c., that the surnames of the sons of Mattathias were simply distinguishing
                    epithets which they bore in ordinary life, and in this light <pb break="no"
                    facs="ia:encyclopediabrit15newyrich/page/n146/mode/1up"
                    xml:id="kp-eb0915-0146-0131"/> “hammerman” appears as a natural surname enough,
                    the occasion of which it would be vain to inquire into. <hi rend="superscript">
                    1</hi> From Judas the name was in later times extended to the whole family, or
                    to the party it represented, or even, as in the title of 3 Maccabees, to other
                    contenders or sufferers for the faith of Israel in the Greek period. The more
                    correct name of the family was Hasmoneans, ’ Aσ[σ]α∕Λo&gt;vαΓoι, ΓP3 (Tgm. Jon.
                    on 1 Sam. ii. 4). According to Josephus, <hi rend="italic">Ant.,</hi> xii, 6, §
                    1, this name is taken from Asamonaeus, the grandfather of Mattathias. Modern
                    writers have suggested a connexion with the townHeshmon (Josh. XV. 27) or with
                    D'30t^∏ <hi rend="subscript"> j</hi><hi rend="italic">magnates,</hi> in Psalm
                    lxviii. 31 [32]. The history of the Hasmoneans is given in <hi rend="smallcaps"
                    >Israel</hi> (vol. xiii. p. 421 <hi rend="italic">sq.)</hi>; in the appended
                    genealogical tables (after Schürer) the dates are those of the death of each
                    individual in years <hi rend="smallcaps">b.c.</hi></p>
                <table>
                    <row cols="1" role="data" rows="1">
                        <cell cols="1" role="data" rows="1"/>
                        <cell cols="1" role="data" rows="1"><p>Mattathias (166).</p></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row cols="1" role="data" rows="1">
