                    </row>
                    <row cols="1" role="data" rows="1">
                        <cell cols="1" role="data" rows="1"><p>(104).</p></cell>
                        <cell cols="1" role="data" rows="1"><p>Jannaeus(78) ∣ Alexandra
                            (69).</p></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row cols="1" role="data" rows="1">
                        <cell cols="2" role="data" rows="1"><p>Hyrcanus II. (30).- Aristobulus II.
                            (49).</p></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row cols="1" role="data" rows="1">
                        <cell cols="2" role="data" rows="1"><p>Alexandra (28) = Alexander (49).
                            Antigonus (37).</p></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row cols="1" role="data" rows="1">
                        <cell cols="2" role="data" rows="1"><p>Aristobulus (35). Mariamme (29), the
                            wife of Herod.</p></cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>The chief authorities are 1 and 2 Maccabees (see next article) and Josephus. For
                    details as to other sources see Schiirer’s <hi rend="italic"
                    >Neutestα-meηtliche</hi><hi rend="italic">Zeitgeschichte,</hi> which gives also
                    a good summary of the history. Of other works subsequent to Ewald’s <hi
                    rend="italic">Geschichte,</hi> vol. iv., it is enough to name.Derenbourg, <hi
                    rend="italic">Histoire</hi><hi rend="italic">de la Palestine</hi> (1867), and
                    Wellhausen’s <hi rend="italic">Pharisäer</hi><hi rend="italic">and</hi><hi
                    rend="italic">Sadducäer</hi> (1874). For the coins of the Hasmoneans see Madden,
                    <hi rend="italic">Coins of the Jews,</hi> 1881.</p>
